{"cursor":"18907","size":15,"audio":[],"currentlang":"en","article":"\n'The Mid-Atlantic Gap' was the undefended area beyond the reach of land-based\nCoastal Command antisubmarine (A/S) aircraft during the Battle of the Atlantic\nin the Second World War. It is frequently known as 'The Black Pit', as well as\nthe Atlantic Gap, Air Gap, Greenland Gap, or just \"the Gap\". This resulted in\nheavy merchant shipping losses to U-boats. The gap was eventually closed in May\n1943, as growing numbers of VLR Liberators (Very Long Range models) and escort\ncarriers became available, and as basing problems were addressed.\n","linknr":323,"url":"Mid-Atlantic_Gap","recorded":1362674079,"links":16,"instances":["raf_officer","navigation","navigation","1943","naval_tactic"],"pdf":[],"categories":["Anti-submarine warfare","Battle of the Atlantic"],"headings":["History","See also","Notes","References"],"image":["//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/e/ec/The_battle_of_the_Atlantic_1941_map.svg/355px-The_battle_of_the_Atlantic_1941_map.svg.png","//bits.wikimedia.org/static-1.21wmf10/skins/common/images/magnify-clip.png","//bits.wikimedia.org/static-1.21wmf10/skins/vector/images/search-ltr.png?303-4","//bits.wikimedia.org/images/wikimedia-button.png","//bits.wikimedia.org/static-1.21wmf10/skins/common/images/poweredby_mediawiki_88x31.png"],"tags":[["battle_of_the_atlantic","1939-1945"],["wolfpack","naval_tactic"],["gee","navigation"],["oboe","navigation"],["washington_conference","1943"],["arthur_harris","raf_officer"]],"members":["arthur_harris","gee","oboe","battle_of_the_atlantic","washington_conference","wolfpack"],"related":["RAF_Coastal_Command","Anti-submarine_warfare","Battle_of_the_Atlantic_(1939-1945)","World_War_II","Greenland","U-boat","Avro_Anson","Vickers_Vildebeest","De_Havilland_Tiger_Moth","RAF_Bomber_Command","Vickers_Wellington","Armstrong_Whitworth_Whitley","Handley_Page_Hampden","Depth_charge","Short_Sunderland","Avro_Lancaster","Consolidated_Liberator_I","